You can do that in your @oauth.tokensetter. The first parameter to that function is a dictionary with various access token parameters that your token setter saves in the database. If you set your user id on that dictionary, it will be returned to the client, e.g.:

@oauth.tokensetter
def save_token(token, request, *args, **kwargs):
  ....
  token['user_id'] = 16

Note: remember that whatever you set on that dictionary must also be serializable into a URL query string, in case those parameters are returned to the client via a browser redirect.

