I do see the reason to why the reactive framework queues all handlers for which all predicates are matched and then runs them even though the state changes during the run. The trigger functionality makes sense then since there might be some operations that won't function properly if the state of the application has changed.

I'm just worried that the proposed syntax for triggers will be hard to grasp for newcomers. @johnsca brought up the idea of having a decorator to force re-checks of predicates to achieve the same result.

Something like this:

```python
@recheck
@when("configured")
def start():
    # This handler can be sure that the charm hasn't
    # removed the configuration during it's current execution.
```

